b97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2806<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/5/03 10:10 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=9.topic>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2001/05/images/021011_nuclear.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  What if Project Orion had not been cancelled?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/images/gallery/npr_orion_to_mars_small.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
How about if Orion had replaced Apollo. Would we now be a spacefaring nation as opposed to a Planet that 'remembers' going to the moon and dreams of Mars? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1768<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/6/03 4:55 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=9.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/user/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What if Project Orion had not been cancelled?</span><hr size=1> I think that both the US and USSR would possess Orion's today.  That we both would have bases on the Moon and Mars, and outposts on soem of the moons of Jupiter and Saturn.  That the cold war would have extended into space.  The USSR might not have collapsed if they were able to mine asteroids, and pummel Afghanistan from orbit.<br>
<br>
Deep Space Force may have become a reality.  Each ship carrying planet buster size nukes as the ultimate in MAD. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zentrander>Zentrander</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 104<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/6/03 7:30 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=9.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What if Project Orion had not been cancelled?</span><hr size=1> Or humanity would be united under one banner right now, mopping up terrorism on its outer reaches, with an interplanetary fleet of trade and exploration ships.  thats my view. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 663<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/7/03 12:58 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=9.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What if Project Orion had not been cancelled?</span><hr size=1> Considering that we have yet to make clean bombs it's possible that we would be living in a radioactive wasteland right now.  I'm assuming all of this would have taken place when above ground nuke testing was still legal and there weren't many environmental restrictions in place.  Then again perhaps only a few mega-orions would have been launched to reduce fall out and a constant barrage of emp blasts.  I'm a support of using orions once they're already in space but not ground launching (at least with today's technology.) <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A> at: 1/7/03 1:00:06 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1773<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/7/03 4:13 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=9.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/user/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What if Project Orion had not been cancelled?</span><hr size=1> One 4000 ton Orion launch would have equalled one small megaton blast in total yield.  Negligible in the 1950's - 60's testing frenzy.  <br>
<br>
Now, I would be in favor of a 'dirty' launch in that time period... it would have made more sense than blowing up nukes just to look at the pretty fireball as with all of the testing.  <br>
<br>
Let's assume that 10 launches took place in the late 1960's.  Each a seperate vehicle, and in the 4000 ton class with 1000 tons of payload.  That would yield a total of 10,000 tons in Earth orbit.  This may have sufficed in order to place a small industry in space that could capture/mine asteroids and produce more Orions and pulse units.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 667<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/7/03 4:56 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=9.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What if Project Orion had not been cancelled?</span><hr size=1> Your right about an Orion launch being insignificant compared to the bombs that were being tested in the time period you mentioned.  I sometimes drift off into lunacy and forget that Orion isn't using 100 megaton bombs.  I think I've been reading too much anti-nuke propaganda recently.  I've been doing research into how the anti-nukers view nuclear power as a source of pollution in space. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zentrander>Zentrander</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 113<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/7/03 5:04 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=9.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top 